    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-05-17T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-05-17T04:00:00-05:00" n="491"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d491">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Control (Korea)/5–1747: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Durbrow</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <gloss target="#t_Niact1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                        </gloss>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-05-17T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >May 17, 1947—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1807. <gloss target="#t_reDeptel1">ReDeptel</gloss> 1155, May 12 to Moscow,
                    repeated Seoul 80, London 2070, Nanking 56 [<hi rend="italic">566</hi>].
                    Following Embassy’s translation text Molotov letter to Secretary dated May 16
                    just received: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Dear Mr. Marshall: I acknowledge receipt of your letter of reply dated
                            May 13, 1947.</p>
                        <p>“Your statement that you are instructing the American Commander in Korea
                            to make immediate preparations for reconvening the Commission <pb
                                facs="0658" n="644" xml:id="pg_644"/> in Seoul I regard as your
                            agreement to my proposal to resume the work of the commission on May 20,
                            1947.</p>
                        <p>“For my part, I inform you that the Soviet delegation to the Joint
                            Commission is prepared to arrive in Seoul by that date.</p>
                        <p>“I am sending copy of this letter to the Govts of UK and the Chinese
                            Republic.</p>
                        <p>“Accept, Mr. Secretary of State, the assurances of my highest
                            consideration. V. M. Molotov”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Sent London as 214. Dept please repeat Nanking as 8 and Seoul as 2.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Durbrow</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
